instructions:
Heat oil in a large pot over medium heat; Add sliced onions and sauté for 3 to 4 minutes until soft and translucent; Add minced garlic and grated ginger; Stir and cook for another 2 minutes until aromatic;
Add chicken pieces into the pot; Stir to coat with the onion mixture; Cook for about 5 to 7 minutes until the chicken starts to brown on all sides;
Sprinkle curry powder evenly over the chicken; Stir thoroughly to coat the chicken with the curry powder; Cook for 2 to 3 minutes to allow the spices to release their aroma;
Pour in the coconut milk; Stir well to combine all ingredients and bring the mixture to a gentle boil;
Lower the heat to a simmer; Cover the pot with a lid and let it cook for 20 to 25 minutes, stirring occasionally; If the curry is too thick, add water gradually to achieve desired consistency;
Taste the curry and add salt as needed; Continue simmering uncovered for another 5 to 10 minutes until the chicken is tender and the sauce thickens slightly;
Turn off the heat; Let it rest for a few minutes before serving.

Rinse the sushi rice under cold water until water runs clear;
Add rice and 2¼ cups water to a pot, bring to boil, then cover and simmer on low for 18 to 20 minutes;
Turn off heat and let rice sit, covered, for 10 minutes;
In a small bowl, mix rice vinegar, sugar, and salt until dissolved;
Transfer rice to a wide bowl, pour vinegar mixture over, and gently fold rice to cool and coat evenly;
Place a sheet of nori, shiny side down, on the bamboo mat;
With wet fingers, spread a thin layer of rice over the nori, leaving 1 inch at the top edge bare;
Arrange a few strips of cucumber, carrot, avocado, and 1 crab stick in a horizontal line near the bottom edge;
Lift the bottom of the mat and roll it tightly over the filling, pressing gently but firmly to shape;
Continue rolling until the exposed edge of the nori seals the roll;
Use a sharp, wet knife to slice the roll into 6 to 8 equal pieces;
Serve with soy sauce, wasabi, and pickled ginger on the side

Trim excess fat from chicken thighs and cut them into bite-sized pieces;
In a bowl, combine soy sauce, mirin, sugar, minced garlic, and grated ginger to make the teriyaki sauce;
Stir well until the sugar is dissolved and set aside;
Heat 1 tbsp of cooking oil in a large non-stick pan over medium heat;
Add the chicken pieces to the pan in a single layer, skin-side down if using skin-on pieces;
Let the chicken cook undisturbed for 4 to 5 minutes until browned on one side;
Flip the chicken and cook the other side for another 4 to 5 minutes until nearly cooked through;
Reduce the heat to low and pour the teriyaki sauce mixture into the pan with the chicken;
Let the sauce simmer with the chicken, turning the chicken occasionally to coat it evenly;
In a small bowl, mix cornstarch with 2 tbsp of water to create a slurry;
Once the sauce starts to bubble, add the slurry to the pan and stir gently;
Cook for another 2 to 3 minutes until the sauce thickens and glazes the chicken nicely;
Drizzle with sesame oil for extra aroma;
Turn off the heat and let the chicken sit in the sauce for a minute to soak in more flavor;
Serve hot, garnished with sesame seeds and chopped spring onion if desired;
Best enjoyed over steamed rice or with stir-fried vegetables.

ingredients:
Water: 4 cups;
Dashi powder (instant soup stock): 1 tsp;
Miso paste: 3 tbsp;
Tofu (firm or silken): 100g, cut into small cubes;
Green onions: 2 stalks, thinly sliced;
Wakame seaweed (dried): 1 tbsp

Shrimp (peeled and deveined): 300g;
All-purpose flour: 1 cup;
Cornstarch: ¼ cup;
Egg: 1;
Ice-cold water: 1 cup;
Baking powder: 1 tsp;
Salt: ½ tsp;
Vegetable oil (for frying): enough to deep fry;
Optional vegetables (sweet potato, bell pepper, green beans): sliced thinly

instructions:
Prepare all ingredients and dry shrimp and vegetables thoroughly;
In a bowl, lightly beat the egg;
Add ice-cold water to the beaten egg; mix gently but do not overbeat;
In a separate bowl, sift together flour, cornstarch, baking powder, and salt;
Add the dry ingredients to the egg mixture slowly; mix lightly with chopsticks or a fork just until combined; lumps are okaydo not overmix or batter will be dense;
Heat oil in a deep pan or fryer to 170-180°C (340-360°F);
Dip shrimp and vegetables into the batter, ensuring they are fully coated;
Carefully place battered items into the hot oil one by one; do not overcrowd the pan;
Fry until the tempura turns light golden and crispy, about 2-3 minutes;
Remove with a slotted spoon and drain on paper towels;
Serve immediately with tempura dipping sauce or soy sauce

ingredients:
Chicken broth: 1.5 liters;
Soy sauce: 4 tbsp;
Miso paste: 2 tbsp;
Sesame oil: 1 tbsp;
Garlic: 3 cloves, minced;
Ginger: 1 inch, minced;
Ramen noodles: 300g;
Chicken breast: 200g, thinly sliced;
Green onions: 3, chopped;
Soft-boiled eggs: 2;
Mushrooms (shiitake or button): 100g, sliced;
Corn kernels: 100g;
Nori (seaweed sheets): 2, cut into strips;
Salt: to taste;
Pepper: to taste

instructions:
Heat sesame oil in a large pot over medium heat; add minced garlic and ginger and sauté until fragrant, about 1-2 minutes;
Pour in chicken broth and bring to a gentle boil; reduce heat to low and stir in soy sauce and miso paste until dissolved;
Add sliced mushrooms and corn kernels to the broth; simmer for 5 minutes to allow flavors to meld;
Meanwhile, cook ramen noodles in a separate pot according to package instructions until just tender; drain and set aside;
In the simmering broth, add thinly sliced chicken breast; cook gently until chicken is fully cooked through, about 5 minutes;
Season broth with salt and pepper to taste;
Divide cooked noodles into serving bowls; ladle hot broth with chicken, mushrooms, and corn over the noodles;
Top each bowl with halved soft-boiled eggs, chopped green onions, and nori strips;
Serve immediately and enjoy your hearty, flavorful ramen!

ingredients:
