instructions:
Drain and rinse soaked chickpeas; pressure cook with enough water and a pinch of salt until soft;
Heat oil in a pan; add cumin seeds and let them splutter; add a pinch of asafoetida; add chopped onions and sauté until golden brown;
Add ginger-garlic paste and green chili; sauté for 2 minutes until raw smell disappears;
Add pureed tomatoes and cook on medium heat until oil separates from the masala;
Add turmeric, red chili powder, coriander powder, and cumin powder; mix well and cook for 2 minutes;
Add cooked chickpeas along with the cooking water; stir and bring to a boil;
Reduce heat and simmer uncovered for 15-20 minutes to thicken the gravy;
Add chole masala and garam masala; mix and cook for another 5 minutes;
Check seasoning and add salt as needed; squeeze lemon juice and stir;
Garnish with chopped coriander leaves; serve hot with bhature, puri, or rice.

ingredients:
All-purpose flour: 2 cups;
Water: 1/2 cup (approx.);
Oil (for dough): 2 tbsp;
Salt: 1 tsp;
Potatoes (boiled and mashed): 3 medium;
Green peas (boiled): 1/2 cup;
Green chili (finely chopped): 1;
Ginger (grated): 1 tsp;
Cumin seeds: 1 tsp;
Coriander powder: 1 tsp;
Garam masala: 1/2 tsp;
Red chili powder: 1/2 tsp;
Amchur (dry mango powder): 1/2 tsp (optional);
Fresh coriander (chopped): 2 tbsp;
Oil (for frying): as needed

instructions:
To prepare the dough, mix flour, salt, and 2 tbsp oil in a bowl; gradually add water little by little and knead into a firm, smooth dough; cover it with a damp cloth and set aside for 30 minutes;
Meanwhile, prepare the filling by heating 1 tbsp oil in a pan; add cumin seeds and let them splutter; add grated ginger and chopped green chili and sauté for a minute;
Add boiled potatoes and green peas to the pan; mix well; add coriander powder, garam masala, red chili powder, amchur powder, and salt; stir everything together and cook for 3-4 minutes; remove from heat and mix in chopped coriander; let the filling cool;
Divide the dough into equal-sized balls; roll each ball into a thin oval or circle about 6-7 inches in diameter; cut the rolled dough into two halves with a knife;
Take one half and form a cone by folding the straight edge corners together; seal the edge by applying a little water; fill the cone with 2 tbsp of the filling;
Seal the open edges of the cone carefully by pressing and folding to form a triangular samosa shape; ensure there are no gaps;
Heat oil in a deep frying pan over medium heat; test the oil by dropping a small piece of doughit should sizzle and rise to the surface;
Fry the samosas in batches, turning occasionally, until they are golden brown and crisp; remove and drain on paper towels;
Serve hot with chutney or ketchup.

ingredients:
Paneer (cubed): 250g;
Thick Yogurt: 1 cup;
Ginger-Garlic Paste: 1 tbsp;
Red Chili Powder: 1 tsp;
Turmeric Powder: 1/2 tsp;
Garam Masala: 1 tsp;
Cumin Powder: 1/2 tsp;
Chat Masala: 1/2 tsp;
Lemon Juice: 1 tbsp;
Salt: to taste;
Oil: 2 tbsp;
Bell Peppers (cubed): 1 medium;
Onion (cubed): 1 medium;
Skewers: as needed

instructions:
Start by preparing the marinade; in a large bowl, whisk together yogurt, ginger-garlic paste, red chili powder, turmeric powder, garam masala, cumin powder, chat masala, lemon juice, salt, and 1 tablespoon of oil until smooth and well combined;
Add the paneer cubes, bell peppers, and onion pieces into the marinade; gently toss everything together so the marinade coats each piece evenly; cover the bowl with cling film and refrigerate for at least 1 hour, allowing the flavors to develop;
Preheat your grill or oven to 200°C (about 400°F); if using an oven, line a baking tray with foil and grease it lightly with oil to prevent sticking;
Thread the marinated paneer cubes alternately with bell pepper and onion pieces onto the skewers; make sure not to overcrowd the skewers for even cooking;
Place the skewers on the tray or grill rack; brush the remaining oil over the paneer and vegetables to keep them moist while cooking;
Grill or bake for 15-20 minutes, turning the skewers halfway through the cooking time to ensure all sides are evenly cooked and slightly charred;
Once cooked, remove from the oven or grill carefully; sprinkle some chat masala and extra lemon juice over the paneer tikka for added tanginess;
Serve hot with green chutney and sliced onions on the side; enjoy your delicious homemade paneer tikka!

