instructions:
Prepare the shrimp by chopping roughly into small pieces; season with salt, sugar, white pepper, and sesame oil; mix well and set aside;
Boil water and pour it gradually over the wheat starch and tapioca starch in a mixing bowl; stir quickly with chopsticks or a spatula to form a dough; let it cool slightly until safe to handle;
Knead the dough with your hands until smooth and elastic; add cooking oil to prevent sticking; cover with a damp cloth to keep moist;
Divide dough into small equal portions; roll each portion into a thin, round wrapper about 3 inches in diameter;
Mix chopped bamboo shoots with soy sauce and cornstarch slurry; add this mixture to the seasoned shrimp; combine gently;
Place a small spoonful of shrimp filling in the center of each wrapper; fold the wrapper in half and pleat the edges to seal, forming a crescent shape;
Prepare a steamer lined with parchment paper or cabbage leaves; place dumplings with some space between them to avoid sticking;
Steam the dumplings over boiling water for 6-8 minutes or until the wrappers turn translucent and the shrimp filling is cooked through;
Serve immediately with soy sauce or chili oil as desired;

ingredients:
Whole fish (such as snapper or sea bass): 1 (about 500g), cleaned and scaled;
Ginger: 3 slices, julienned;
Green onions: 2 stalks, cut into 5cm pieces;
Soy sauce: 2 tbsp;
Sesame oil: 1 tbsp;
Cooking oil: 2 tbsp;
Salt: 1/2 tsp;
White pepper: a pinch;
Fresh cilantro (optional): for garnish

instructions:
Clean the fish thoroughly and pat dry with paper towels; season the fish inside and out with salt and white pepper;
Place half of the ginger slices and one stalk of green onion inside the fish cavity; arrange the fish on a heatproof plate suitable for steaming;
Scatter the remaining ginger and green onion on top of the fish; prepare a steamer by bringing water to a boil;
Place the plate with fish into the steamer carefully; cover the lid tightly and steam over high heat for about 8 to 10 minutes, depending on fish thickness;
Check for doneness by inserting a fork or chopstick at the thickest part  to  the flesh should flake easily and be opaque;
While the fish is steaming, heat cooking oil in a small pan until hot but not smoking;
Once fish is cooked, carefully remove the plate from the steamer; drizzle soy sauce and sesame oil evenly over the fish;
Pour the hot cooking oil over the fish and garnish with fresh cilantro if desired; serve immediately.

ingredients:
Cooked rice: 3 cups;
Carrot: 1, julienned;
Zucchini: 1, julienned;
