instructions:
Prepare all vegetables by washing and cutting as described; blanch spinach and bean sprouts separately in boiling water for about 1 minute each, then rinse with cold water and squeeze out excess moisture; season spinach and bean sprouts lightly with salt, minced garlic, 1 tsp sesame oil, and a bit of soy sauce, mixing well;
Heat 1 tbsp vegetable oil in a pan over medium heat; sautée carrots until slightly softened, about 2-3 minutes; remove and set aside; repeat this step for zucchini and mushrooms, cooking each separately to keep flavors distinct; season each sautéed vegetable lightly with salt and a little soy sauce;
In a small bowl, mix gochujang with sugar and 1 tsp sesame oil to make the spicy sauce;
Fry eggs sunny-side up in a non-stick pan with a little oil, keeping yolks runny;
To assemble, place cooked rice at the bottom of a large bowl; arrange each vegetable neatly on top of the rice in sections; place the fried egg in the center; drizzle sesame oil over the top; sprinkle sesame seeds;
Serve with the gochujang sauce on the side; mix everything well before eating for the best flavor combination.

ingredients:
Korean rice cakes (tteok): 400g;
Fish cakes: 150g, sliced;
Gochujang (Korean chili paste): 3 tbsp;
Gochugaru (Korean chili flakes): 1 tbsp;
Soy sauce: 2 tbsp;
Sugar: 1 tbsp;
Garlic: 2 cloves, minced;
Water: 3 cups;
Green onions: 2, chopped;
Boiled eggs: 2 (optional);
Sesame oil: 1 tsp;
Sesame seeds: 1 tsp (for garnish);

instructions:
Soak the rice cakes in warm water for 10 minutes if they are hard or refrigerated;
In a large pan, add water, gochujang, gochugaru, soy sauce, sugar, and minced garlic;
Stir the sauce mixture well to dissolve the gochujang completely;
Bring the sauce to a boil over medium-high heat;
Add the rice cakes and fish cakes to the boiling sauce;
Reduce the heat to medium and let it simmer, stirring occasionally to prevent sticking;
Cook for about 10-15 minutes or until the rice cakes become soft and chewy;
If using boiled eggs, add them in the last 5 minutes to warm through;
Once the sauce thickens to a glossy, sticky consistency, stir in chopped green onions and sesame oil;
Turn off the heat and sprinkle sesame seeds on top before serving;
Serve hot as a snack or meal with optional boiled eggs on the side;

